{meta: title The Old Lamplighter}
{meta: artist Jim Ed Brown}
{meta: composer Charles Tobias and Nat Simon}

{start_of_verse: Verse 1}
[C]He made the [F]night a little [C]brighter
[E7]Wherever he would [Am]go
The [F]old lamp [C]lighter  of long [D7]long [G7]ago
His snowy [F]hair was so much [C]whiter
[E7]Beneath the candle glow [Am]the old [F]lamp [C]lighter
Of long [G7]long [C]ago
{end_of_verse}

{start_of_verse: Verse 2}
You'd hear the patter of his feet
{end_of_verse}

{start_of_verse: Verse 3}
As he came toddling down the street
{end_of_verse}

{start_of_verse: Verse 4}
His smile would hide a lonely heart you see
If there were sweethearts in the [F]park
{end_of_verse}

{start_of_verse: Verse 5}
He'd pass a lamp and leave it dark
Remembering the days that used to [G7]be
For he recalled when things were [C]new
{end_of_verse}

{start_of_verse: Verse 6}
He loved someone who loved him too
Who walks with him alone [G7]in [C]memories
{end_of_verse}

{start_of_verse: Verse 7}
He made the [F]night a little [C]brighter
[E7]Wherever he would [Am]go
The [F]old lamp [C]lighter of long [G7]long [C]ago 
{end_of_verse}

{start_of_verse: Verse 8}
Now if you look up in the sky
{end_of_verse}

{start_of_verse: Verse 9}
You'll understand the reason why
{end_of_verse}

{start_of_verse: Verse 10}
The little stars at night are all aglow
He turns them on when night is [F]near
{end_of_verse}

{start_of_verse: Verse 11}
He turns them off when dawn is here
The little man who lived so long [G7]ago
{end_of_verse}

{start_of_verse: Verse 12}
